Part I - Ford Go Bike Data Exploration¶

Introduction¶

Ford GoBike is a publicly available dataset that includes information about individual rides made in a bike-sharing system covering the greater San Francisco Bay area. The dataset can be downloaded from here

The data contains the following information(columns) for each individual ride:

  • duration_sec - this is trip duration in seconds
  • start_time- Start Time and Date for the trip
  • end_time -End Time and Date for the trip
  • start_station_id - Start Station ID
  • start_station_name - Start Station Name
  • start_station_latitude - Start Station Latitude
  • start_station_longitude - Start Station Longitude
  • end_station_id - End Station ID
  • end_station_name - End Station Name
  • end_station_latitude - End Station Latitude
  • end_station_longitude - End Station Longitude
  • bike_id - Bike ID
  • user_type- (Subscriber or Customer Subscriber = Member or Customer = Casual)
  • member_birth_year - Member Year of Birth
  • member_gender - Member Gender
  • bike_share_for_all_trip - boolean value with yes and no values

Data cleaning¶

Here we will address the following data quality and tidiness issues that we have encountered so far;

  • there are missing values in station information columns
  • change datatype of the following columns
    • start_time and end_time datatype need to be changed to datetime
    • convert bike_id datatype to string
    • Convert the start_station_id and end_station_id to int64
    • convert member_birth_year to int64

Issue #1 : Missing values¶

  • Define: Drop the missing Values

Code:

Dataset Structure¶

The dataset is a dataframe with features of indivual ride in the columns and each row is a trip ride. There are 183412 fordgobike trips in the dataset with the following 16 features: duration_sec, start_time, end_time, start_station_id, start_station_name, start_station_latitude, start_station_longitude, end_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_latitude ,end_station_longitude, bike_id, user_type, member_birth_year, member_gender, bike_share_for_all_trip.

The main feature(s) of interest in the dataset are:¶

  • duration_sec - this is trip duration in seconds
  • start_time- Start Time and Date for the trip
  • end_time -End Time and Date for the trip
  • start_station_name - Start Station Name
  • end_station_name - End Station Name
  • user_type- (Subscriber or Customer Subscriber = Member or Customer = Casual)
  • member_birth_year - Member Year of Birth
  • member_gender - Member Gender

In the above features am interested in understanding how the trip duration is related to them.

The following features in the dataset will help support my investigation into feature(s) of interest¶

  • Trip duration relies mostly on the start stations and end stations.
  • User_type, birthyear and gender also effect trip duration.

def boxgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    #creating box plots with seaborn's PairGrid
    default_color = sb.color_palette()[0]
    sb.boxplot(x, y, color = default_color)

plt.figure(figsize = [10, 10])
g = sb.PairGrid(data = bike_df, y_vars = 'duration_sec', x_vars = ['user_type', 'member_gender', 
                                                                         'bike_share_for_all_trip'],

g.map(boxgrid)
plt.ylim([0,5000])
plt.show();

Bike share for all trip tends to be similar on average across all types .

           palette = 'Blues', linestyles = '', dodge = 0.4)
plt.title('Trip Duration across week days and user type')
plt.ylabel('Average Trip Duration (Secs)')
plt.xticks(np.arange(0, 7 + 1, 1),weekday_labels)
ax.set_yticklabels([],minor = True)
plt.show();

Observation: Subscribers travel short trips in the weekdays compared to weekends. Customers trip duration is not affected by the day of the week.

Conclusions¶

  • The dataset is just for the month of February 2019

  • The average duration for all trips is about 600 seconds

  • Most trips were taken on Tuesdays and Thursdays

  • Users with the age of 30 years tend to have the longest trips

  • Weekends have the least trip records

  • The morning hours (8 and 9 hrs) and the evening (17 and 18 hrs) have the highest trip records

  • Most of the trips were taken by subscribers

  • Very few trips were bike sharing for all trips

  • Most of the trips were taken by males

  • Customers spend more duration than subscribers

  • Females spend more duration than males

  • Trip durations on weekends are longer than on other weekdays

  • Only subscribers are allowed to share bikes on trips

  • Customer type doesn't really affect the number of trips per weekday

  • Customers travel for longer durations regardless of the day of the week as compared to subscribers.
